  "interpretation": {
    "rt_traversal_overhead": "OptiX traversal overhead is not the blocker at the 32k Qwen shape. The selector plus CUDA rerank is about 13-14 us for 8 to 288 synthetic queries.",
    "sequential_layer_cost": "If a semantic selector had to run once per Qwen layer, the selector plus rerank estimate is about 0.47-0.49 ms/token before descriptor update cost.",
    "data_dependency": "Qwen layer queries are produced after each layer input is known, so true semantic RT retrieval cannot use the current one pre-graph OptiX launch unless it uses stale or non-semantic descriptors.",
    "missing_piece": "The missing implementation is a real page-descriptor acceleration structure over Qwen KV/page summaries plus a layer-aware launch path that feeds live query descriptors into OptiX and returns candidate page ids to the existing selected-page attention."
  },
  "conclusion": "RT cores remain viable for candidate selection, but current Qwen sparse RT is still synthetic. The next proof must integrate real page descriptors and live layer queries; current evidence does not support claiming semantic RT retrieval yet."
